5:[["$","$L10",null,{}],["$","main",null,{"children":["$","div",null,{"className":"py-16 px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8","children":["$","div",null,{"className":"max-w-2xl mx-auto","children":[["$","$L11",null,{"href":"/blog","className":"inline-flex items-center gap-2 text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 hover:text-gray-900 dark:hover:text-white transition-colors mb-10","children":[["$","svg",null,{"ref":"$undefined","xmlns":"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg","width":24,"height":24,"viewBox":"0 0 24 24","fill":"none","stroke":"currentColor","strokeWidth":2,"strokeLinecap":"round","strokeLinejoin":"round","className":"lucide lucide-arrow-left w-4 h-4","aria-hidden":true,"children":[["$","path","1l729n",{"d":"m12 19-7-7 7-7"}],["$","path","x3x0zl",{"d":"M19 12H5"}],"$undefined"]}],"Field Notes"]}],["$","header",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"text-xs font-medium text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 mb-3","children":"Operations"}],["$","h1",null,{"className":"text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-4 balance","children":"Lost and Found Workflows That Help Reunite Pets Faster"}],["$","time",null,{"className":"text-sm text-gray-400 dark:text-gray-500","children":"Mar 5, 2025"}]]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"prose-like","children":[["$","p","0",{"className":"text-base text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4","dangerouslySetInnerHTML":{"__html":"Most reunifications happen in the first 24-48 hours after a pet goes missing. After that, the chances of finding an owner drop significantly. This means the speed of your lost and found workflow directly determines outcomes."}}],["$","h3","1",{"className":"text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mt-8 mb-3","children":"The matching problem"}],["$","p","2",{"className":"text-base text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4","dangerouslySetInnerHTML":{"__html":"The hard part of lost and found isn't collecting reports — it's matching them. A lost report and a found report about the same animal might use completely different descriptions. \"Brown lab mix\" and \"tan short-haired dog.\" Same animal, different descriptor."}}],["$","p","3",{"className":"text-base text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4","dangerouslySetInnerHTML":{"__html":"Manual matching requires someone to read every new report against every open report and make a judgment call. For a shelter handling dozens of reports per week, this becomes a full-time job."}}],["$","h3","4",{"className":"text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mt-8 mb-3","children":"A structured intake form"}],["$","p","5",{"className":"text-base text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4","dangerouslySetInnerHTML":{"__html":"The first improvement is standardizing how reports come in. Instead of a free-text \"describe your pet\" field, a structured form collects:\n- Species, breed, primary color, secondary color\n- Sex, estimated age\n- Microchip number (if known)\n- Last known location (address + date)\n- Distinguishing marks\n- Collar/tag description\n- Photo (required)"}}],["$","p","6",{"className":"text-base text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4","dangerouslySetInnerHTML":{"__html":"Structured fields make matching possible. \"Brown\" and \"tan\" are still a judgment call, but matching by species + approximate color + location + date is much more tractable than matching free text."}}],["$","h3","7",{"className":"text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mt-8 mb-3","children":"The follow-up protocol"}],["$","p","8",{"className":"text-base text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4","dangerouslySetInnerHTML":{"__html":"Most reunifications happen because someone follows up — calls shelters, posts in neighborhood groups, checks back. A workflow that surfaces open reports to staff daily, sorted by age, ensures no report sits dormant."}}],"$L12","$L13","$L14","$L15","$L16","$L17"]}],"$L18"]}]}]}],"$L19"]
12:["$","p","9",{"className":"text-base text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4","dangerouslySetInnerHTML":{"__html":"In Open Paw, open lost/found reports appear in the coordinator's task list until they're marked resolved. The match status moves through: open → potential match → confirmed → reunited or closed."}}]
13:["$","h3","10",{"className":"text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mt-8 mb-3","children":"When to involve the public"}]
14:["$","p","11",{"className":"text-base text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4","dangerouslySetInnerHTML":{"__html":"Some organizations publish lost and found reports publicly. This is often the right call — the person who found a dog is more likely to see a public listing than to call a shelter. But public listings require care: full contact information for the reporting party should not be public. A contact form or email relay protects privacy while enabling contact."}}]
15:["$","h3","12",{"className":"text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mt-8 mb-3","children":"The outcome measure"}]
16:["$","p","13",{"className":"text-base text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4","dangerouslySetInnerHTML":{"__html":"Track your reunification rate. What percentage of lost reports result in a confirmed reunion? What's the average time from report to reunion? These numbers tell you whether your workflow is working."}}]
17:["$","p","14",{"className":"text-base text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4","dangerouslySetInnerHTML":{"__html":"Most organizations that move from ad-hoc reporting to a structured workflow see their reunification rate improve. The workflow doesn't find lost pets — the community does — but the workflow makes sure nothing falls through the cracks."}}]
